title: Plants of Jollys Road, Anakie
description: This collection contains records of plant species observed from along Jollys Road in Anakie, including the roadside and the 18-hectare Trust for Nature covenanted property of 25 Jollys Road.

items.title: Polycarpon tetraphyllum
items.content_text: An occasional weed of disturbed, often gravelly areas.

items.title: Pterostylis smaragdyna
items.content_text: Many tens of plants both flowering and sterile. Higher density than observed in past.

items.title: Chrysanthemoides monilifera subsp. monilifera
items.content_text: Cluster of seedlings arising from fox scat containing almost solely the seed of Boneseed.

items.title: Olearia pannosa subsp. cardiophylla
items.content_text: Severely browsed by wallabies. One of only two plants of this species found in the near vicinity. The plant was caged to protect from Wallaby browsing. The other plant is also caged and approximately 30 metres away.

items.title: Olearia pannosa subsp. cardiophylla
items.content_text: One of only two plants of this species found in the near vicinity. The plant was caged to protect from Wallaby browsing. The other plant is also caged and approximately 30 metres away.

items.title: Clematis decipiens
items.content_text: Flammuliform leaf is the key feature for C. decipiens. C. microphylla s.s. is trifoliolate, having 3 sets of usually 3 leaflets with a total of 9-11 leaflets per leaf. ID confirmed by Neville Walsh.

items.title: Isolepis spp.
items.content_text: Maybe Isolepis cernua subsp. platycarpus. ID by Neville Walsh.

items.title: Pterostylis sp. aff. revoluta (Inland)
items.content_text: Large Autumn Greenhood. Woodland/Open Forest habitat.

items.title: Senecio pinnatifolius var. lanceolatus
items.content_text: A seedling that recruited following the Jan 2006 wildfire.

items.title: Lobelia gibbosa sensu Walsh  Albrecht & Knox (2010)
tags: id~Lobelia gibbosa sensu Walsh  Albrecht & Knox (2010)

items.title: Papilio aegeus aegeus
items.content_text: The female Orchard Swallowtail adult butterfly that visited Jollys Road in summer 2011 must have laid an egg. This observation was made on the same lemon tree where the butterfly was observed.
